Reason: To predict the melting point of N-(3-Bromo-4-nitrophenyl)acetamide, let's consider the effect of each functional group on the basic unit, benzene. The basic benzene ring has a melting point around 5.5°C. Adding a nitro group (+NO2) would typically increase the melting point due to its electron-withdrawing nature and the introduction of a strong dipole, which we can approximately estimate as +80°C. The presence of a bromine atom (+Br) also tends to raise the melting point because of increased molecular weight and the polarizability of the bromine atom, adding about +40°C. The acetamide group (CH3CONH-) is an amide linkage, and due to the possibility of hydrogen bonding and resonance stability, this can further increase the melting point significantly by around +50°C. These adjustments are additive because they all contribute independently to the molecular stability and lattice energy.
